{{Infobox royalty | name = Nunasokonakatsu-hime | succession = [[Empress consort of Japan]] | reign = 546–510 BC (36 years) | predecessor = [[Isuzuyori-hime]] | successor = [[Amonotoyototsu-hime]] | spouse = [[Emperor Annei]] | issue = [[Tokotsuhikoirone]] [[Emperor Itoku]], [[Ikisomimi no mikoto]] [[Shikitsuhiko]] | father = [[Kamo no Okimi]] | mother = [[Mirahime]] | succession1 = [[Empress dowager of Japan]] | reign-type1 = 510 BC-? | predecessor1 = Isuzuyori-hime | successor1 = Amonotoyototsu-hime }}
'''Nunasokonakatsu-hime''' (渟名底仲媛命) was Empress Consort from 546-510BC<ref>Anston, p., 41 (Vol. 1)</ref><ref name=":0">and Anston, p. 1.42 (Vol. 1)</ref> and then Empress Dowager from 510BC to an unknown date. <ref name=":0" /> == Life == There exact number of children differs between the [[Kojiki]] and [[Nihon Shoki]]. In the Kojiki they have 3, Tokotsuhikoirone, Emperor Itoku, and Shikitsuhiko.<ref name=":1">Yasumaro. O, translated by Gustav Heldt. (2014) “Kojiki. An Account of Ancient Matters”. New York: Columbia University Press.</ref> Yet in the Nihon shoki they have another, Ikisomimi.<ref name=":2">W. G. ASTON, C.M.G. (1896) “Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697”. Tuttle Publishing.</ref> only the Kojiki states her father as Kamo no Okimi. <ref name=":1" /><ref>Ponsonby, F. (1959) “The Imperial House of Japan.” Kyoto: Ponsonby Memorial Society.</ref> The Empress's life isn't recorded in the Kojiki or Nihon shoki much other than her family and titles. <ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Nunasoko Nakatsuhime • . A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/nunasoko-nakatsuhime/ |access-date=2024-03-21 |website=. A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |language=en-GB}}</ref>
